    <div class="content-section">
        <section id="Sindhudurg Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Sindhudurg Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sindhudurg Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Sindhudurg Fort is a historical sea fort located on a rocky island off the coast of Malvan in Sindhudurg district, Maharashtra. Built by the Maratha ruler Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj in the 17th century, it served as a naval base and a strategic defense point against foreign invasions. The fort is known for its impressive architecture, including 42 bastions, high walls, and hidden entrances. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Tarkarli Beach" class="section">
            <h2>Tarkarli Beach</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Tarkarli Beach" class="section-image">
            <p>Tarkarli Beach, located in the Sindhudurg district of Maharashtra, is a popular tourist destination known for its pristine white sand beach, clear blue waters, and opportunities for water sports like scuba diving and snorkeling. It's a great place for a family vacation, offering a blend of natural beauty, historical attractions, and local culture. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Vijaydurg Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Vijaydurg Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Vijaydurg Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Vijaydurg Fort, located in Sindhudurg district, Maharashtra, is a historic coastal fort known for its strategic location and impressive architecture. It was a key naval base, particularly under Maratha rule and the Angre family. The fort is situated at the mouth of the Vaghotan River, and is surrounded by the sea on three sides, making it a formidable structure. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Devbagh Beach & Tsunami Island" class="section">
            <h2>Devbagh Beach & Tsunami Island</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Devbagh Beach & Tsunami Island" class="section-image">
            <p>Devbagh Beach and Tsunami Island, both located in Sindhudurg, Maharashtra, offer unique attractions for tourists. Devbagh Beach is known for its serene and clean beach, perfect for relaxation and enjoying the confluence of the Karli River and the Arabian Sea (Devbagh Sangam). Tsunami Island, a small island formed near the delta of the Tarkarli River, is a hub for water sports and boat rides in the backwaters. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sawantwadi Palace" class="section">
            <h2>Sawantwadi Palace</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sawantwadi Palace" class="section-image">
            <p>The Sawantwadi Palace, located in Sindhudurg, Maharashtra, is a historic royal residence built by Khem Sawant III between 1755 and 1803. It's a popular tourist attraction known for its architecture, art, and cultural significance. The palace is a blend of English arches and native craftsmanship, featuring bricked brown walls, a central square facade, extensive gardens, and a man-made lake. It also houses a boutique art hotel offering immersive experiences in history, art, and cuisine. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Kunkeshwar Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Kunkeshwar Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Kunkeshwar Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>Kunkeshwar Temple, dedicated to Lord Shiva, is an ancient temple located in the Kunkeshwar village of Sindhudurg district in Maharashtra. It's situated about 14 km from Devgad town and is known as the "Kashi of South Konkan". The temple is believed to have been built by the Yadav Kings in 1100 AD. It's known for its unique architecture, featuring tall stone walls that taper towards the Shikhar (spire). </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Amboli Waterfalls" class="section">
            <h2>Amboli Waterfalls</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Amboli Waterfalls" class="section-image">
            <p>Amboli Waterfall, located in the picturesque Amboli Ghat hill station of Sindhudurg district, Maharashtra, is a popular tourist attraction known for its scenic beauty and cascading waters, especially during the monsoon season. It's a great spot for nature lovers and adventure seekers, offering a refreshing escape with its cool waters and misty atmosphere. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sateri Devi Jal Mandir & Other Shrines" class="section">
            <h2>Sateri Devi Jal Mandir & Other Shrines</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" class="section-image">
            <p>Dedicated to the local deity Sateri, the temple is believed to have been built in the 12th or 13th century. It was originally surrounded by a lake, giving it the name "Jal Mandir" (water temple), though the lake has since receded. The deity is believed to be in the form of an anthill, which, according to legend, started bleeding when struck by a buffalo, leading to the construction of the temple.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="Rock Garden (Malvan)" class="section">
            <h2>Rock Garden (Malvan)</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Rock Garden (Malvan)" class="section-image">
            <p>The Rock Garden in Malvan, Sindhudurg, is a unique garden built on a rocky beach, offering a tranquil space with lush greenery and sculptures made from waste materials. It's known for its beautiful sunset views and is a popular spot for relaxation and photography. The garden also features a small playground for children and is located near Chivla Beach. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Napne Waterfall Glass Skywalk" class="section">
            <h2>Napne Waterfall Glass Skywalk</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Napne Waterfall Glass Skywalk" class="section-image">
            <p>The Glass Bridge at Napne waterfall features high-strength transparent glass. Therefore, visitors crossing the bridge can look directly at the water below. The bridge has vibrant and dramatic arches and railings as well as a large butterfly sculpture. The location is full of natural beauty on all sides.</p>
            <p></p>
        </section>
